g.title: Folded Corner.205
g.desc: The Chain Of Responsibility pattern compliments the Open Clos...

g.text: The Chain Of Responsibility pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by decoupling sender from its receivers. This enhances stability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where the sender ‘knows’ all its receivers and decides who handles the request. Stability, because the Chain of Responsibility (COR) pattern allows adding new Handlers to the ‘chain’ without modifying the other handlers directly. This has positive impact on test and production code of the Handlers. The COR realizes this stability via an abstraction between handlers and the use of dependency injection. For comparison; localizing the handler logic inside the original sender would require the sender to change when a new receiver(=Handler) must be added.

g.text: The order, type and number of objects, to handle a request sequentially, should be modifiable during runtime

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: The Chain of Responsibility pattern prescribes unfamiliarity ...

g.text: The Chain of Responsibility pattern prescribes unfamiliarity between sender and receiver. The receiver is not statically bounded to the sender, but can be dynamically assigned during runtime. This provides the advantage to re-order or add/remove Handlers within the chain of Handlers. In contrast, a single sender, directly associated with multiple receivers and coordinating the request across those receivers, would not be modifiable during runtime.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Chain of Responsibility entails both the negative and pos...

g.text: The Chain of Responsibility entails both the negative and positive aspects of the Single Responsibility principle. The pattern distributes the request-handle logic across multiple Handlers. This makes comprehending the whole chain (who handles what?) more difficult, because logic is scattered. As a result readability is degraded.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The Chain of Responsibility pattern shifts the responsibility...

g.text: The Chain of Responsibility pattern shifts the responsibility, of knowing which receiving objects should handle a request, from a single sender to each respective receiver. This distributes the decision logic across receivers making them transceivers. Each transceiver, called a ‘Handler’, knows if it can handle a request and calls the next handler if it cannot. Each handler, can be coupled to another, because they follow a common abstract Handler. Spreading the responsibility from a single sender to multiple transceivers reduces the dependency model of the original sender. This allows the original sender to be re-used just like every other handler. However, the ‘chaining’ of handlers is distributed to client code, making the client more complex. An example of the Chain of Responsibility pattern: a ‘hover-over’ help option in the UI could be displayed via a Button element. In case the Button does not specify this help ‘behavior’ it passes the request to its parent: Dialog. If the Dialog cannot handle it, then it will be passed to the Application.

g.title: Folded Corner.239
g.desc: The Chain Of Responsibility compliments the Single Responsibi...

g.text: The Chain Of Responsibility compliments the Single Responsibility pattern by distributing request-handle logic. This enhances testability, reusability and stability. All aspects are compared against an implementation where the sender knows all its receivers and decides who handles the request. This implementation often results in high cyclomatic complexity. Testability, because each branch of the original sender’s request-handle logic is distributed and can now be tested in a relative small problem window (=handler). Also, the original sender has less dependencies making the sender easier to test. Stability, because the logic is distributed along a chain of handlers. This mitigates the risk of breaking something unrelated to the change. Reusability, because the original sender contains less dependencies making it more reusable to other clients (=handlers). The original sender, that has now become a handler, can be re-used in other chains as well.

g.title: Folded Corner.244

g.text: The Chain of Responsibility pattern allows decomposition of conditional structures. Conditional structures (e.g.: switch-case or if-else) are a representation of the Chain of Responsibility pattern. The Chain Of Responsibility pattern prescribes decomposing conditional structures into a object like representation. Each object may handle a request and/or pass the request along the chain. This object oriented approach enhances reusability, testability and flexibility.
